<br>
I will say it. If you remember, the WTC was attacked in 1993 when <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Clinton</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was in office. It just didn't fall down and go boom that time (but the plan was to bring it down and we just got lucky that time).<br>
<br>
I am not sure how the rest of the county is doing at this point, but where I am working things are going much better. This time last year we had 56 employees. Today we have 162 employees. We just all got big fat raises, and we all walked into work last Monday to find that our 17&quot; computer monitors had all been replaced with 21&quot; flat plasma monitors. We have 100% tution reimbursement (new benefit for this year), free medical insurance for us and family, and it pays 90% of everything (well, it doesn't cover boob jobs or sex changes) including drugs.<br>
<br>
I check out www.monster.com from time to time to see what is up there, and over the last few months I have been seeing more jobs listed, and some actually pay decent amount. I have seen several for different management/IT/IS/etc listed that pay 80k+  so someone is doing some hiring and paying out some bucks. I would say things are getting better, and not just because of cuts in workforce, etc.<br>
<br>
<br>
To elaborate on the miltary thing: When I got out (which was in 1989) I was making around $1800.00 (USD) a month as an E-4 and Gharb was right: I had free housing, free utilities, I got BAS and spent around $90 a month on food at the commissary. I had free health care, free college classes, free prescriptions, I got 30 days of leave a year plus EVERY government holiday off, sick days did NOT get taken out of your leave, and only had to worry about gas and insurance. The rest was to spend <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  If you chose not to take leave, you could sell it back for cash. I am sure that anyone with more than 2 years in would make even more since there is always a cost of living increase every year, and I am sure wages have gone up in the last 14 years. E-1 doesn't make very much, but I had no complaints about my pay when I was in.<br>
JMO, donning flame resistant gear now.<br>
